					<description><![CDATA[For some time, it appeared that the dreaded &#8220;RRoD&#8221; had overlooked my Xbox 360 console. Over the years, I&#8217;ve watched as my brother, friends, family members, and co-workers had to send their consoles into Microsoft for warranty repair. Â Sometimes even on multiple occasions. Â The ruthless crimson-ringed beast seemed to spare no one. Â In fact, I&#8217;m [&#8230;]]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>For some time, it appeared that the dreaded &#8220;<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xbox_360_technical_problems#.22General_Hardware_Failure.22_errors">RRoD</a>&#8221; had overlooked my Xbox 360 console.</p>
<p>Over the years, I&#8217;ve watched as my brother, friends, family members, and co-workers had to send their consoles into Microsoft for warranty repair. Â Sometimes even on multiple occasions. Â The ruthless crimson-ringed beast seemed to spare no one. Â In fact, I&#8217;m almost positive that I do notÂ know a single person that has an early-model Xbox that has not &#8220;red ringed&#8221; at some point.</p>
<p>On Thursday night, as I went to launch my newly downloaded Battle Field 3 beta, my Xbox beeped loudly and froze up. Â I powered it off, and powered it back on &#8211; only for it to freeze at the Xbox boot screen animation. Â A second power off/on showed me a most unpleasant site framed in a very distinctly reddish hue. Â It seemed, much like death itself stalking the cast of a Final Destination movie, that this unmerciful demon of console demise had at last found its misguided way to my Xbox</p>
<p><a href="http://ericvb.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/rrod_evil-e1317658213222.jpg"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1516" title="rrod_evil" src="http://ericvb.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/rrod_evil-e1317658213222.jpg" alt="" width="349" height="349" srcset="http://www.ericvb.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/rrod_evil-e1317658213222.jpg 349w, http://www.ericvb.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/rrod_evil-e1317658213222-150x150.jpg 150w, http://www.ericvb.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/rrod_evil-e1317658213222-300x300.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 349px) 100vw, 349px" /></a></p>
<p>Personally, I feel this has been a long time coming. Â I&#8217;ve somehow managed to dodge this bullet for years. Â Probably the fact that I have the &#8220;2nd printing&#8221; of the Xbox 360 Pro with an HDMI port bought me this extra lease on life, but who can be sure. Â After a night&#8217;s rest, the RRoD continued in the morning. Â I decided it was time to take corrective actions. Â Microsoft extended warranty coverage for this issue for a period of 3 years. Â Since I bought my Xbox in November of 2007, I was 11 months past my warranty coverage. Â This leaves my 1st option: Â Send the console into Microsoft for 100 dollar repair/refurb.</p>
<p>Since I like 100 dollars in my bank account, I did not even consider this option.</p>
<p>My next thought is to replace the console. Â I immediately shop on Amazon and Newegg, but I&#8217;m not really enjoying the notion of paying $200 plus for a new Xbox and paying for a data migration kit.</p>
<p>A third option, much more my style, began to creep into my frazzled mind. Â  &#8220;Why not try to actually try to fix this myself?&#8221;. Â I am a fairly technically savvy person with a family history of MacGyvering &#8211; so I saw fit to AT THE VERY LEAST lace up, touch gloves, and slug it out for a few rounds with the RRoD. Â I commenced work immediately.</p>
<p>I didn&#8217;t use a guide to open up my Xbox; but I should have. Â I used brute force and a couple of plastic tabs that hold the top plastic bezel in place are now snapped off. Â It was difficult to Â get this console open my first time, and it probably took me 45 minutes to have the thing completely disassembled to where I had the system board out and all other pieces off to the side.</p>
<p><a href="http://ericvb.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/rrod_disassembled.jpg"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-1513" title="rrod_disassembled" src="http://ericvb.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/rrod_disassembled-e1317658875780-300x300.jpg" alt="" width="300" height="300" srcset="http://www.ericvb.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/rrod_disassembled-e1317658875780-300x300.jpg 300w, http://www.ericvb.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/rrod_disassembled-e1317658875780-150x150.jpg 150w, http://www.ericvb.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/rrod_disassembled-e1317658875780.jpg 481w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></a></p>
<p>With everything opened up and my warranty (or, possibility of ever having one) now completely devoid, I started looking at possible fixes. Â Both the CPU and GPU heat-sinks seemed firmly attached, so I didn&#8217;t believe that to be my problem. Â Overall, the system was pretty clean. Â I blew out some of the dust plugging up the fans and heat-sinks overall, but that definitely wasn&#8217;t enough of a backup to cause a RRoD in my opinion.</p>
<p>So, I decided it must be the memory chips on the bottom of the Xbox system board. Â These 4 chips sit on the bottom side where no fan/cooling will ever reach them. Â Microsoft tried to alleviate this by attaching someÂ chintzy thermal pads, but those things were basically a band aid with some high density foam attached to the chips.</p>
<p>I removed the pads and cleaned the memory chips. Â I used <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=wsz0lNJ6JrQ&amp;t=4m18s">this guide</a> to replace those pads with some custom &#8220;penny based&#8221; copper heat sinks. Â You take 2 pennies, wrap them together with electrical tape, and stick them onto those 4 memory chips. Â From the pic, you can see I have a tube of high-temperature synthetic grease which I layered between the chip and pennies.</p>
<p>The entire process was a pain. Â Getting the system back together was harder than taking it apart. Â It&#8217;s difficult to get everything to line up correctly while keeping those pennies in place on the chips. Â After I got it part-way back together, I test-booted the Xbox only to find that the red ring persisted. Â Even worse, this time it seemed to red ring before even powering on the fans. Â I took this to mean that I had a short somewhere; and indeed it did seem that the system board was crooked from my penny application. Â I adjusted screw tension in several places, and removed screws completely in other places &#8211; and after someÂ finagling I was able to get the system to boot to it&#8217;s &#8220;normal&#8221; red ring where the fans and everything at least had power.</p>
<p>Further research indicated that the RRoD error code may persist even if you have fixed the problem. Â The easiest way to clear that error code was to replace it with another error code and/or reset the onboard chips. Â The easiest way to do THAT is to simply overheat your Xbox. Â Shouldn&#8217;t be too hard, right? Â I mean, the thing runs at nuclear temperature even in a ventialted area. Â Google reported the &#8220;towel trick&#8221; was the key, and I watched <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=avWs4-wD15w">this entertaining guy</a> do said trick &#8211; which apparently means cooking your Xbox for 20-25 minutes.</p>
<p>Since I had the thing apart already, I decided to expedite this baking process by booting it up without the fans installed. Â So I turned it on, then wrapped the console in a thick fleece blanket, and about 6 minutes later it completely powered off. Â I tried to boot it up again, and I got 2 red rings vs 3 (indicating overheat, yay!). Â So, I let it cool off for about 10 minutes before trying again&#8230;</p>
<p><a href="http://ericvb.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/rrod_remedied.jpg"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-1514" title="rrod_remedied" src="http://ericvb.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/rrod_remedied-e1317660311581.jpg" alt="" width="600" height="440" srcset="http://www.ericvb.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/rrod_remedied-e1317660311581.jpg 600w, http://www.ericvb.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/rrod_remedied-e1317660311581-300x220.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 600px) 100vw, 600px" /></a></p>
<p>It BOOTED!!! Â I let it idle for a bit, played some Trials, verified live connectivity, etc etc. Â Everything was looking great! Â The penny fix in combination with an overheat to clear it out seemed to do the trick for me.</p>
<p>I put the unit back together, and by this point I was very comfortable getting it back together correctly. I tightened all the screws, got all the tabs back in place, buttoned it up completely.</p>
<p>With everything hooked back up; I tested the console for awhile playing various games. Â I played Trials. Â I played Battlefield 3 beta. Â I reviewed my settings and live connectivity again&#8230; Â  And after 1-2 hours, it was still working fine.</p>
<p>I have continued playing throughout the weekend with 2-3 hours per session;Â totalingÂ probably 8-10 hours ofÂ game play; and I feel like everything is very stable. Â No more red rings. Â I have done multiple power on/offs, disconnected/reconnected all hardware and storage devices; and at this time I feel very good about my Xbox and its &#8220;Non RRoD&#8221; status.</p>
<p>In fact, everyone in the family does!</p>
<p><a href="http://ericvb.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/rrod_everybodyshappy.jpg"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1515" title="rrod_everybodyshappy" src="http://ericvb.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/rrod_everybodyshappy.jpg" alt="" width="392" height="523" srcset="http://www.ericvb.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/rrod_everybodyshappy.jpg 392w, http://www.ericvb.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/10/rrod_everybodyshappy-224x300.jpg 224w" sizes="(max-width: 392px) 100vw, 392px" /></a></p>
<p>Take that, RRoD&#8230; Â I looked through your intimidating vengeful red eye directly into your villainous soul. Â After a hard-fought battle, I am confident that on this day, Â good has triumphed over evil&#8230;</p>
<p><strong>###UPDATE###</strong><br />
This penny fix was only temporary. Â The red-ring of death resurfaced about 10 days later and asked me for a rematch.</p>
<p>This time I pulled out all the stops and researched every possible fix that typically works for the RRoD. Â Ultimately, I ended up at 2 main fixes:</p>
<ul>
<li>Replacing the X-clamps that hold the heat syncs in place for the GPU and CPU, combined with replacing theÂ thermal paste on the cores/heatsinks</li>
<li>Purchase a heat gun and use it to refresh the solder connections by heating the bottom of the circuit board.</li>
</ul>
<p>I followed this video tutorial pretty much exactly. Â He does a great job explaining the work done, and gives exact specs for the hardware that replaces the crappy X-clamps. Â I took it one step further and drilled a grid of holes in the top of my Xbox to improve the airflow over top of the heatsinks.</p>
<p><iframe loading="lazy" width="480" height="360" src="http://www.youtube.com/embed/uB2QoJM7p5I?rel=0" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen></iframe></p>
<p>This work seems to have officially bested the RRoD &#8211; as of now it&#8217;s been operating for about a month without any further issues. Â I&#8217;ve also noticed it running much quieter now that I&#8217;ve drilled the holes, so I think that has improved the airflow and makes it so my fans have to do much less work to move the same amount of air.</p>
<p>Your move, RRoD.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
