					<description><![CDATA[A couple months ago, I was blogging about my exploration into the world of internet radio and streaming music.Â  I was enthusiastically trying new services and overall just making a push to find a better way to experience music.Â  I was weighing pros and cons of a few different services over this time, and I&#8217;m [&#8230;]]]></description>
										<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>A couple months ago, I was blogging about my <a href="http://www.ericvb.com/archives/my-evolution-of-music">exploration into the world of internet radio and streaming music</a>.Â  I was enthusiastically trying new services and overall just making a push to find a better way to experience music.Â  I was weighing pros and cons of a few different services over this time, and I&#8217;m happy to emphatically proclaim that <a href="http://www.pandora.com">Pandora radio</a> is by far the best service for me.Â </p>
<p>I purchasedÂ the annualÂ subscription to the premium Pandora One service, and it is possibly the best 36 dollars that I&#8217;ve ever spent.Â  The premium service grants several enhancements; most important areÂ the ad-free listening, a desktop application, and higher quality audio streams.Â  For a clean and simple to use service, it&#8217;s amazing what somebody can get from Pandora.Â  I supremely enjoy the fact that I can queue up an endless stream of music that is specifically tailored to my tastes; all while not having to worry about creating playlists or syncing up any media devices.</p>
<p>Not only has Pandora simplified the way I listen to music, but it&#8217;s drastically expanded my exposure.Â  Before Pandora, I had very specific musical tastes.Â  I grew up listening to only a handful of what the music had toÂ offer, and that basicallyÂ trained me to keepÂ in a &#8220;sheltered&#8221; state of music.Â  I was overly picky and I never gave anything new a chance.Â  I didn&#8217;t know that KillswitchÂ Engage&#8217;s song &#8220;Holy Diver&#8221; was a cover ofÂ  Dio.Â  I didn&#8217;t know Dio sang for Black Sabbath.Â  I didn&#8217;t know or appreciate what Jimi Hendrix could do on a guitar.Â  I didn&#8217;tÂ enjoy the vintage appeal of bands like Led Zeppelin or the Rolling Stones.Â  I didn&#8217;t graspÂ the depth of genre that has come with the lastÂ decade or so in music.</p>
